You are an expert reviewer evaluating hierarchical decompositions of benchmark problems. You output ONLY a single JSON object: {"verdict": "acceptable" | "needs revision", "justification": "<one to two sentences>"}.

A decomposition is "acceptable" if:
- "global" captures the overall plan in one sentence,
- the union of subtasks covers what the problem actually asks for,
- atomics under each subtask are operational steps that, executed in order, would complete that subtask,
- "global_atomics" contains only steps that genuinely cross subtasks (verification, final checks, etc.),
- gold_actions mirrors the same structure with specific resolved actions.

It "needs revision" if any of the above fail clearly.

Output ONLY the JSON object, with no prose before or after, no markdown fencing.

</system>

Benchmark: WorkArena++
Domain: web agent / Airlines (Mind2Web proxy — WorkArena++ unavailable on HF)

Full problem:
Compare all membership tier benefits.

Candidate v2 hierarchy:
{
  "global": "Navigate to the airline loyalty program membership tiers page and systematically extract and compare the listed benefits for every tier.",
  "subtasks": [
    {
      "subtask": "Locate the membership tiers overview page",
      "atomics": [
        "Open the airline website homepage",
        "Identify and click the loyalty/frequent-flyer program navigation link",
        "Find and click the 'Membership Tiers' or 'Benefits' sub-navigation link"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Enumerate all available membership tiers",
      "atomics": [
        "Scrape or read all tier names displayed on the page (e.g., Basic, Silver, Gold, Platinum)",
        "Confirm the total count of distinct tiers"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Extract benefits for each membership tier",
      "atomics": [
        "For each tier, collect all listed benefit labels and descriptions",
        "Record quantitative benefit values where present (e.g., bonus miles percentage, lounge access count, upgrade priority level)",
        "Note tier-specific exclusive benefits not shared with lower tiers"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Construct a side-by-side comparison of tier benefits",
      "atomics": [
        "Align benefits into a common attribute list across all tiers",
        "Mark which tiers include each benefit (present / absent / conditional)",
        "Highlight incremental benefits gained at each tier upgrade"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "global_atomics": [
    "Verify that no tier has been omitted by cross-checking the extracted tier list against any tier-selector UI element or dropdown",
    "Confirm the comparison table covers every benefit category shown on the page"
  ]
}

Candidate v2 gold_actions:
{
  "global": "Click through the airline site's loyalty program navigation to the membership tiers benefits page, read all tier names and their associated benefit rows, and produce a structured comparison matrix.",
  "subtasks": [
    {
      "subtask": "Locate the membership tiers overview page",
      "atomics": [
        "Click the homepage URL of the airline web application",
        "Click the 'Loyalty Program' or 'Frequent Flyer' top-nav menu item",
        "Click the 'Membership Tiers' or 'Compare Benefits' link in the sub-menu or hero section"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Enumerate all available membership tiers",
      "atomics": [
        "Read all tier heading elements (h2/h3 or tab labels) to obtain the ordered list of tier names",
        "Assert the count of detected tier names matches the number of tier columns or sections rendered"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Extract benefits for each membership tier",
      "atomics": [
        "For each tier column or section, read every benefit row label and its corresponding value or checkmark",
        "Parse numeric qualifiers such as '2x miles', '4 lounge passes/year', or 'Priority 1 upgrades'",
        "Flag benefits marked as exclusive (e.g., 'Elite only', 'Top Tier exclusive') per tier"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Construct a side-by-side comparison of tier benefits",
      "atomics": [
        "Build a benefit-keyed dictionary mapping each benefit attribute to a per-tier value list",
        "Fill absent benefits with a null/false marker so all tiers share the same attribute keys",
        "Compute and label delta benefits — attributes that first appear at each successive tier"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "global_atomics": [
    "Re-read the tier selector tabs or navigation pills to confirm all tier names in the comparison matrix are present and none were missed",
    "Scroll the full benefits table to ensure no benefit rows are hidden below the fold or behind a 'Show more' toggle before finalising the comparison"
  ]
}

Output the JSON verdict now.

